    explanation: "**Antimicrobial stewardship** — central to modern infectious disease + surgical practice. WHO top 10 global health threats includes antimicrobial resistance. Drivers: overuse, misuse, broad-spectrum overreliance, agriculture, lack of new antibiotics. **5 Rs of antibiotic use**: 1. **Right diagnosis** — culture before antibiotic when feasible 2. **Right drug** — narrow when organism known 3. **Right dose** — patient-specific 4. **Right duration** — shortest effective (recent evidence supports shorter courses for many infections; e.g., 5-7 days for uncomplicated pneumonia, abdominal infection if source control adequate) 5. **Right route** — IV-to-oral conversion early when patient stable + absorption adequate **De-escalation** — switch from broad to narrow when sensitivity known. **Source control** — surgical/IR drainage, debridement, device removal — critical; antibiotic alone often inadequate. **Common resistant organisms (priority)**: 1. **ESKAPE** pathogens — common nosocomial multi-drug resistant: - Enterococcus (VRE) - Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) - Klebsiella pneumoniae (ESBL, CRE) - Acinetobacter baumannii (MDR/XDR) - Pseudomonas aeruginosa (MDR) - Enterobacter species 2. **Candida** including auris (emerging MDR) **New antibiotics**: - Ceftolozane-tazobactam (Pseudomonas, ESBL) - Ceftazidime-avibactam (CRE, KPC) - Meropenem-vaborbactam (CRE) - Imipenem-relebactam - Eravacycline (CRE, Acinetobacter) - Cefiderocol — siderophore cephalosporin (CRE, Acinetobacter) - Tedizolid (MRSA, VRE) - Delafloxacin **Stewardship program elements** (CDC core elements): leadership commitment, accountability, drug expertise, action (prospective audit + feedback, formulary), tracking, reporting, education. **MRSA decolonization** (CHG bathing + mupirocin nasal) — reduces SSI + MRSA infections in select surgical populations (cardiac, orthopedic). **Allergy delabeling** — important: > 90% of self-reported penicillin allergies are NOT true IgE allergies; delabeling enables use of effective + narrow first-line agents. **C. difficile prevention**: minimize broad-spectrum + duration; contact precautions; hand hygiene (soap > alcohol for C. diff spores); environmental cleaning.",
