    explanation: "**Organ donation** — central to transplantation; complex ethical, legal, medical framework. **Types**: 1. **Deceased donor**: - DBD (Donation after Brain Death) - most common - DCD (Donation after Circulatory Death) - increasing 2. **Living donor**: kidney (most common), liver lobe, lung lobe, others 3. **Tissue donation**: corneas, skin, bone, heart valves **Brain death** (death by neurologic criteria): - Cause of coma known + irreversible - Confounders excluded (hypothermia, drugs, severe metabolic) - Clinical exam: coma, absent brainstem reflexes, positive apnea test - Confirmatory studies as needed (EEG, cerebral blood flow, angiogram) - Uniform Determination of Death Act (US) + similar laws globally **DCD**: - Maastricht categories I-V (controlled vs uncontrolled) - Withdrawal of life support → asystole → declaration of death (typically 5 min observation) → rapid organ recovery - Warm ischemia time critical for organ viability - Expanding pool — outcomes good for kidney + liver; recently good for heart + lung with NRP (Normothermic Regional Perfusion) **Living donation**: - Kidney most common (~ 30-40% of US transplants) - Liver lobe (right or left lobe — adult-to-adult, left lateral segment adult-to-child) - Donor evaluation comprehensive — medical, psychological, social, financial - Independent donor advocate - Long-term donor follow-up + outcomes tracking - Slight increase in long-term ESRD risk in kidney donors (still low absolute risk) **Ethical principles**: 1. Dead donor rule — vital organs only from confirmed dead 2. Voluntary consent — no coercion, no payment 3. Separation of teams — donor care team independent from recipient/transplant 4. Family approach by OPO + sensitive 5. Equitable allocation 6. Respect for autonomy + patient wishes **Donor management**: aggressive resuscitation post-brain death → optimize organ function for procurement (hemodynamic, hormonal — thyroid, steroid; lung protective ventilation; glycemic control). **OPO + OPTN/UNOS** (US): coordinate, allocate, regulate. **Increasing donation strategies**: opt-out systems (Spain has highest donor rates globally), public education, family discussions, donor registry awareness, required request laws, hospital protocols. **Newer**: extended criteria donor (ECD), hepatitis C+ donor to + recipient with subsequent DAA cure, paired exchange (living kidney swap), domino transplant.",
